abstract: CHICAGO, June 30 -- Scared speculators had to pay 60 cent. interest to-day for money to carry wheat. Liquidation was on a stupendous scale. It was the last day before the long-anticipated July delivery, and marked a crisis in the wheat trade. Numbers of unlucky traders had held on to their July wheat, hoping for some bulge or spurt on the bull side to let them out.

abstract: TOPEKA, Kan., July 3 -- The strike of the coal miners in Kansas and Missouri is fast assuming a dangerous condition. The strikers are determined that no outside miners shall be permuted to work, and they are especially determined that negroes shall not be imported for that purpose. They declare that if the operators carry out their expressed intentions and employ negro miners there will be violence.

abstract: CHICAGO, Ill., July 8. -- Wheat speculators are looking for a bullish Government crop report on Monday afternoon, and they advanced wheat lo bushel today on the faith of what they expect. abstract: TOPEKA, Kan., July 8. -- Mrs. Laura M. Johns, President of the Kansas Equal Suffrago Association, has issued an address in which she announces that the suffrage campaign has began. abstract: GEORGE FORRESTER died in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., Monday night. He was born in Ridgebury, Conn., in 1818. He left there when twelve years old to seek his fortune in this city, where an elder brother had already established himself in the dry goods business. Entering as a clerk, in course of a few years he was taken into partnership, and still later on became sole proprietor of the business.

abstract: -- A party of wheelmen from Eastern, Penn., passed through this city Sunday on their return from an interesting bicycle trip. They were J. Wallace Ingham, Quintus F. abstract: CHICAGO, July 18 -- Ed Corrigan's Tyro, handsomely ridden by Fred Tarsi, captured the Maiden Stakes to-day at Washington Park. The stake was worth $3,000 to the winner. Decapod and Linda were next in demand at 5 to 1 each.

abstract: NEW-LONDON, July 19. -- Last Saturday a fleet of more than thirty yachts of the Atlantic Yacht Club started out of Cold Spring Harbor to cruise to the eastward. abstract: CHICAGO, July 19. -- Wheat went to smash worse than ever to-day. There was a break of over 2c a bushel in the December option. abstract: JERSEY CITY, N.J., July 22. -- George Shars of Glen Gardner, N.J., to day told Chief of Police Murphy he had been swindled out of $200 by "green-goods" men whom he met at Taylor's Hotel. abstract: NEW-YORK, MONDAY, July 24 -- P.M. The bears raided the market at the opening to-day, and with considerable success, as there were apparently no buying orders. But the moment pressure relaxed the recovery was quite as pronounced as had been the previous weakness. After the first hour the market became steady and very dull. Toward the close, however, the bear leaders became aggressive once more, and the final dealings were marked by weakness and irregularity.

abstract: CAMP WERTS, SEA GIRT, N. J., July 25 -- First Lieut. Albert Van Walraven is in command of Company C of the Second Regiment. abstract: CAMP WERTS, SEA GIRT, N. J., July 26. -- The hottest day of the year at Camp Werts opened at 7 o'clock this morning with the thermometer at 91. abstract: CITY OF MEXICO, July 26. -- One most extraordinary feature of the present deranged condition of the silver market is that American sliver bullion is beginning to be imported for coinage into Mexican dollars. The French fleet with M. Pavie. French Minister Resident, have gone to Kon-si-Chang.

abstract: -- Roanoke College, Va., has just celebrated the close of its fourth decade, and rejoices greatly in its prosperity. Its friends say it never received a single dollar of income from invested endowment funds during its first three decades. Bequests had been left, but none of them became available until 1883, and the professors were supported almost exclusively from the income from tuition fees.

abstract: ROCHESTER, N.Y., July 27. Dr. George Fiacher, who has resided in this city since 1881, committed suicide last night by drinking an ounce of Hydrate of chloral. That the doctor premeditated suicide there is no doubt, because he left on his desk a certificate of his own death, filled out in his own handwriting, and in the space "Reported by" he had inserted "him-self."

abstract: CHICAGO, July 28 -- Utler demoralization characterized the wheat market throughout the session to-day and all previous records for low prices were again broken. One firm is reported as paying as high as 3 1/2 c a bushel to carry over a large line of wheat into September.

abstract: PATERSON, N.Y., July 28 -- While Patrick McVilla, sexton of St. John's parochial school, was trimming shrubbery in the Catholic cemetery, a spark from his pipe ignited the withered grass, and soon flames spread in all directions, enveloping him and the monuments around. McVilla pulled his cap over his ears and made a break through the fire, half blinded and half suffocated by the smoke.

abstract: The Marsh Family Association of this country is composed of descendants of seven of that name who emigrated to America between 1633 and 1675, all coming from England, and settling in Massachusetts and Connecticut. It is believed that their descendants to-day number 200,000. abstract: LOCKPORT, N. abstract: The French naval manoeuvres for 1893 ended on July 28. The period of manoeuvre extended over nine days. The manoeuvre work was confined mostly to the Mediterranean. abstract: NEW-YORK, MONDAY, July 31 -- A.M. Last week was one of considerable interest in Stock Exchange circles. For the first time in many weeks the bears met with opposition, but it did not come until they had pretty much everything their own way.
